1. Business Understanding

This data set was made with the intention to predict and prevent studen dropouts and failures in higher education. The data contains basic information about the student and their parents, including socio-economic and demographic information.

Using this data, we aim to identify factors that may be correlated to an increased probability of a student dropping out and/or failing out of college or university. It would also be useful to identify which factors may indicate a higher probability of student success. If the factors are something in the student's control, these results can be used by employees in higher education to help students who may be at a higher risk of leaving higher education prematurely. The results could also be used by various non-profits and tutoring companies to aid students who are high risk.

Colleges and universities could use this data to increase retention rates. SMU, specifically the Lyle School of Engineering, could utilize this data to make efforts in The Recruitment and Retention Office more effective.

Measure of Reliability

https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/10056943

In this article, the researchers sought to predict student performance in higher education. In the literature review section, they referenced multiple other studies that had been done using machine learning. A few of those descriptions included the accuracy of the prediciton models used; in the first, the accuracy was 76.37-82.39%, and on the second, there was an accuracy of 74%. Based on these results, our prediction algorithm should have an accuracy of 75% or greater to be on par with other pre-existing machine learning models.

2.2 Data Quality

Before we could perform task on this dataset, we must first ensure the quality of the dataset and fix any inconsistency. The following code is going to check if the dataset contained any missing data and creating a matrix plot to visualize any missing hole within the dataset.

In[124]:
import matplotlib.pylab as plt
import missingno as mn
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

mn.matrix(df)
plt.title("Matrix Plot", fontsize=22)
plt.show()

As to why we care about duplication. Considering some of the criterial taken by this data set. The chance that 2 student have the exact same information such as martial status, course, Nationality, and gender is fairly plausible given most of these information can have a level of systematic bias due to where and how the research is performed. But information such as parental, background, and grades related features (i.e. Mothers Occupations, Fathers Occupation, 1st semester grades, 2nd semester grades) are statically improbable to be completely the same, especially if it span over all features.

In[125]:
# Find the duplicate instances (excluding the first occurrence)
idx = df.duplicated()

# Find the number of duplicate instances
num_duplicates = idx.sum()  # Sum of 'True' values gives the count of duplicates

print(num_duplicates)

15

Given that only 15 instances was found and within those duplications, there are only a few overlaps, we decided that keeping all 15 instance in the data set was fine. Our justification was that for a dataset of 4424 total entry, 15 case is only 0.339% of the data set, negligible in comparison. Yes, the statistical chance of duplication in this research is very unlikely. But since 15 is such a small percentage within a grand total of 4424, by shear chance or a divine joke by god, 2 person who are different somehow have the same life isn't completely impossible. We believe that in worst case scenario, these 15 entry were simply systematic error. Having 0.339% of the data count more than once wont really affect the grand scheme of things, the consequence is insignificant.

Lastly, as you will see from the data visualization in the next section, even though the data set has no missing values, there are some irregularity with some of the values that might create issue for a machine learning application. An example would be the "Histogram of 1st Semester Grades" where you have a very high amount of 0. We understand why there could be grade of 0 in the data set. So if a student never even finish their first semester or that they are a transfer student, or they just straight up bombed their first semester, its hard to speculate why there are the way they are. But due to the consistency and quantity of these data, we dont want to eliminating or imputing these data since that will most definitely change the overall result of the data set. So our still going to include them. But depending on the application, we could do parse the data set into sub data set without these irregularities.

# 4. Correlation between 1st and 2nd semester grades
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))

# Ensure that grades are properly converted to numeric for both semesters
df['Curricular units 1st sem (grade)'] = pd.to_numeric(df['Curricular units 1st sem (grade)'], errors='coerce')
df['Curricular units 2nd sem (grade)'] = pd.to_numeric(df['Curricular units 2nd sem (grade)'], errors='coerce')

# Filter out the rows where both grades are 0 (no meaningful correlation)
df_filtered = df[(df['Curricular units 1st sem (grade)'] != 0) &
                 (df['Curricular units 2nd sem (grade)'] != 0)]

# Rename 'Dropout' to 'Student Type' for clarity
df_filtered = df_filtered.rename(columns={'Dropout': 'Student Type'})

# Plot filtered data
sns.scatterplot(x='Curricular units 1st sem (grade)', y='Curricular units 2nd sem (grade)',
                hue='Student Type', data=df_filtered, palette='coolwarm')

plt.title('Correlation between 1st and 2nd Semester Grades')
plt.xlabel('1st Semester Grade')
plt.ylabel('2nd Semester Grade')
plt.show()

# Calculate correlation
correlation = df_filtered['Curricular units 1st sem (grade)'].corr(df_filtered['Curricular units 2nd sem (grade)'])
print(f"Correlation between 1st and 2nd semester grades: {correlation:.2f}")

# Calculate average grades for dropouts and graduates
avg_grades = df_filtered.groupby('Student Type')[['Curricular units 1st sem (grade)', 'Curricular units 2nd sem (grade)']].mean()
print("\nAverage grades for dropouts and graduates:")
print(avg_grades)

# Calculate percentage of students who improved their grades
improved = (df_filtered['Curricular units 2nd sem (grade)'] > df_filtered['Curricular units 1st sem (grade)']).mean() * 100
print(f"\nPercentage of students who improved their grades: {improved:.2f}%")

# Print some basic statistics
print("\nBasic statistics for 1st semester grades:")
print(df_filtered['Curricular units 1st sem (grade)'].describe())
print("\nBasic statistics for 2nd semester grades:")
print(df_filtered['Curricular units 2nd sem (grade)'].describe())

def draw_umap(n_neighbors=15, min_dist=0.1, n_components=2, metric='euclidean', title=''):
    fit = umap.UMAP(n_neighbors=n_neighbors,
                    min_dist=min_dist,
                    n_components=n_components,
                    metric=metric)
    u = fit.fit_transform(data)
    fig = plt.figure()
    if n_components == 1:
        ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
        ax.scatter(u[:,0], range(len(u)), c=data)
    if n_components ==2:
        ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
        ax.scatter(u[:,0], u[:,1], c=data)
    if n_components ==3:
        ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
        ax.scatter(u[:,0], u[:,1], u[:,2], c=data)
    plt.title(title, fontsize=18)

Interpreting Results

With our data set, there doesn't appear to be a strong corrleation between certain variables. Most clusters seem to be color specific, meaning that variables are related to themselves strongly, but not necessarily with other variables. Using the n_neighbors value of 15 and the min_dist value of 0.1 (traditionally accepted values according to https://github.com/lmcinnes/umap/tree/master), there are not strongly clustered groups, meaning that most instances are not strongly associated together.

Explanation of UMAP dimensionality reduction methods

Dimensionality reduction is used to aid in visualizing and understanding the relationship between many variables in a dataset. When there are only a few variables (e.g. x and y on a traditional cartesian plane), it is easy to see the correlation between the two variables simply by graphing it. However, it becomes harder to visualize the relationship between variables when the number of variables increases above 3. Dimenionality reduction helps portray multi-dimensional variable relationships in a 1d, 2d, or 3d manner so that it is easier to see the relationship between many variables all at once.

The variable min_dist affects how closely points can be compressed together. Large values for min_dst will make the points more loosely clustered, causing the model to lose some detail and decreases the visibility of the global structure of the data.

The variable n_neighbors determines how globalized the clusters are. The more neighbors, the better global view one will have of the data. The fewer neighbors will result in a more localized view with more detail, but it will be more difficult to see the overall structure of the data set.

UMAP begins by first creating a version of a weighted graph, where the weights are the probability that two instances are connected. Each point has a radius that extends from it, and when two radii intersect, the points connect. UMAP uses the n_neighbors variable to control the length of these radii, meaning that each radius is selected locally. UMAP also requires that all instances are connected to at least one other instance (the interactive graph above will produce an error if you try to make n_neighbors=0), and this helps to make sure that both the local and global structures are preserved.
